<HL>
   Five Firms Called
   For Questioning
   On Fuel-Price Rise
   ----
   By Paul M. Barrett
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
OIL, INTEGRATED MAJORS (OIL)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
ENERGY DEPARTMENT (ERG)
FEDERAL TRADE COMMISSION (FTC)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Justice Department said it called in
three major oil refiners and two independent gasoline
marketers for questioning about the big price jump since
Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
   The department said it's looking for possible price-fixing
or other antitrust violations. James Rill, the department's
antitrust chief, declined to identify the five companies but
said more companies will be interviewed in the inquiry.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "We are getting cooperation from the oil companies," he
said at a news briefing yesterday, indicating that compliance
with the investigation has been voluntary.
   Such confidential questioning is typical in the
preliminary stages of an antitrust investigation.
   At this point, the inquiry is focusing on the entire U.S.
petroleum-products industry, rather than on particular
companies, Mr. Rill added.
   Federal officials will decide within four weeks whether to
take the further step of making compulsory demands for
documents from target companies or convening a grand jury to
consider criminal charges, Mr. Rill said. A team of 10
Justice Department lawyers and economists are looking into
the possibility of collusion by major oil companies and
price-gouging by distributors and retailers, he said.
   The American Automobile Association said its most recent
national survey found that the average price of gasoline at
the pump jumped 15% from Aug. 1, the day before the invasion,
to Aug. 20. The average pump price of unleaded regular
gasoline jumped to $1.237 from $1.075 over that period, the
AAA reported.
   State attorneys general, as well as officials from the
Federal Trade Commission and U.S. Department of Energy, are
working with the Justice Department. Scores of members of
Congress, as well as state officials, have criticized big oil
companies for recent increases in gasoline prices.
   In a statement issued late yesterday, the American
Petroleum Institute defended the industry's pricing. Despite
the market turmoil since the Iraqi invasion, "members of the
petroleum industry have been trying to act with restraint and
responsibility," the trade group said. As evidence, it
asserted that the 16-cent-a-gallon increase in gasoline pump
prices since the invasion compares with a rise of about 25
cents a gallon for spot-market crude prices and 35 cents a
gallon for spot-market gasoline prices.
   "In other words, the pump price for gasoline increased by
a considerably smaller amount than have the costs oil
companies must pay to replenish those supplies," the
statement said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900824-0085
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900824-0085.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Retailers, Nike Say Boycott
   Isn't Harming Firm's Sales
</HL>
<DATE>
08/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   NIKE
</CO>
<IN>
TEXTILES AND APPAREL (TEX)
</IN>
<LP>
   Operation PUSH's call for a nationwide boycott of Nike
Inc. athletic shoes and other products apparently hasn't had
much impact so far.
   Several retailers who sell Nike items report that
consumers for the most part are ignoring the civil rights
group's boycott call. Many customers don't even seem aware of
it, they say.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Nike's stock has taken a pounding since the boycott was
announced, dropping $2 yesterday in over-the-counter trading
to close at $62. But analysts said the declines had more to
do with investor nervousness over the possibility of war in
the Middle East and fears that a recession is imminent.
   Ray Cabillot, an analyst with Piper Jaffray &amp; Hopwood,
said he hasn't altered his forecast that Nike will earn $7.25
a share on revenue of $2.7 billion for the year ending next
May. Last fiscal year, Nike earned $243 million, or $6.42 a
share, on revenue of $2.2 billion.
   A spokeswoman for the athletic apparel maker said sales in
Chicago, where Operation PUSH is based, have increased since
the boycott call.
   PUSH called for the boycott because it says Nike gets
about 30% of its more than $2 billion in annual revenue from
black customers but invests little in black communities. Last
week, Nike announced a series of affirmative-action programs
that PUSH officials then denounced as inadequate.
   A spokeswoman for PUSH said its boycott is working and
that the impact on sales probably won't show up until Nike's
next quarter.
</TEXT>
