<HL>
   Technology &amp; Medicine:
   Apple Prepares
   To Introduce
   3 Computers
   ---
   New Line Is Said to Include
   Color Macintosh Model
   At Sharply Lower Price
   ----
   By G. Pascal Zachary
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   MSFT HWP AAPL SNE
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   Apple Computer Inc. has set plans for introducing three
new computers in mid-October, including the company's first
Macintosh computer with a detachable color monitor that will
sell for a "street" price of roughly $2,500, according to
people familiar with Apple's plans.
   Earlier this year, Apple came under fierce criticism for
sticking with an aging family of lower-cost computers and for
offering color models only at prices above $4,000 at a time
when many color models compatible with International Business
Machines Corp.'s PC sell for below $2,000. John Sculley,
Apple's chief executive officer, has repeatedly defended the
company's move into higher-priced, higher-performance
products. But in February, he forced out his chief of product
development and added those duties to his own.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Apple's three new computers will be the first to be
introduced by the Cupertino, Calif., concern since Mr.
Sculley took over product development. Prices for the
products, all Macintosh computers, haven't been established.
But people familiar with Apple's plans say the products
include a replacement for the company's venerable Macintosh
Plus, a new Macintosh with a detachable color monitor priced
at roughly $2,500 and a high-end machine that's basically a
slimmed-down version of its hot-selling Macintosh IIci.
   Apple won't comment on the future products, though it
confirmed that it plans a major product introduction in
October.
   Industry observers say the new products could represent a
watershed for Apple because if they don't sit well with
customers the company may decide to abandon its proprietary
approach to computing. Today, Apple doesn't license its
system software, which controls the basic operations of its
Macintosh computers, to other companies.
   Senior executives at Apple lately have been studying new
ways of doing business. The company's executives are even
privately asking whether Apple should be licensing its
proprietary software. That software is the key to Apple's
success, but it also prevents Macintosh owners from using the
vast number of software programs written for IBM's PC.
   The most important of the new computers is the Macintosh
LC, a mid-range, color model that offers some distinctive
advantages over the company's low-end Macintosh SE, but none
of the power of its higher-priced color models.
   The LC will use Motorola Inc.'s 68020 microprocessor and
will have room for added electronics gear that will enable it
to run software written for the company's incompatible Apple
II computers. Observers, who declined to be identified, say
Apple hopes to regain some of the momentum it has lost this
year with educational customers who want to buy Macintoshes
but balk at prices for various models.
   While Apple hopes to win back education customers with the
LC, it plans to continue to sell Apple II machines, say
people familiar with the company's plans.
   But the LC probably won't be shipped to customers until
next January, partly because Apple is scrambling to secure
sufficient quantities of color monitors from its chief
supplier, Sony Corp., said one industry executive who asked
not to be identified. Any delay in shipping the LC could
complicate things for Apple because it could result in
customers holding off on purchases of existing models.
   People familiar with the discussions say Apple won't make
drastic shifts in its proprietary approach now. They say
Apple's senior management wants to see the reception given
its forthcoming models before altering its course.
   Even if the new products sell well, however, the company
still could shift gears. For months, some analysts have urged
Apple to begin selectively licensing its system software,
arguing that Apple will benefit from competitors' selling
machines that use Macintosh software. "Who knows what event
will push Apple into doing that?" asked Michelle Preston, an
analyst at Cowen &amp; Co. "It could be any number of things."
   Separately, a federal judge in San Francisco put off
deciding some potentially major issues in Apple's copyright
infringement suit against Microsoft Corp. and Hewlett-Packard
Co. Apple claims operating system programs of the two
companies are too similar to the "look and feel" of its
Macintosh system and yesterday had sought a ruling that its
copyrights were valid.
   Microsoft and Hewlett-Packard have contended that the
Macintosh visual displays aren't original enough to be
deserving of much protection under the copyright laws and
that their products were largely covered by license
agreements with Apple, among other arguments. Judge Vaughn
Walker didn't indicate when he would rule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900824-0083
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900824-0083.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Cedar Group Expects
   Gardenbolt Purchase
   Will Pay Off Soon
</HL>
<DATE>
08/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   PHILADELPHIA -- Cedar Group Inc. expects to realize
marketing and management benefits "almost immediately" from
its acquisition of Gardenbolt International Corp., said
Lawrence Rutstein, chairman.
   Earlier this week, Cedar Group announced its agreement to
acquire Gardenbolt, a Sayerville, N.J., distributor of
imported fasteners, for $5.5 million. Gardenbolt had 1989
sales of about $26 million. The transaction is expected to be
completed next month.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Rutstein said Cedar Group believes the move will help
the company expand its market share significantly at a time
when the industrial-fasteners industry is consolidating and
sales growth is generally "stagnant or flat." In the U.S.,
industry sales of imported nuts, bolts and other fasteners
exceeded $1 billion in 1989.
   "Gardenbolt is a major step for us," Mr. Rutstein said in
an interview. "It puts us into the top tier of distributors
in the country."
   Cedar Group would also gain an experienced management team
"that can help us as we make additional acquisitions," Mr.
Rutstein said. Under terms of the agreement, Steven
Schonholtz, president and chief executive of Gardenbolt, will
become executive vice president and chief operating officer
of Cedar Group.
   Mr. Rutstein said Gardenbolt, with more than 50 years of
experience in the fasteners industry, has "an excellent
reputation that can help us attract other companies to our
nest."
   Moreover, the product-line mixes of the two companies
complement each other. Cedar Group, which anticipates sales
in the range of $18 million to $20 million in fiscal 1991
ending Jan. 31, concentrates on bulk marketing of internally
threaded products, such as nuts and washers.
   In contrast, Gardenbolt handles a broad line of screws and
externally threaded bolts. It generally sells them in smaller
quantities at higher margins and to different categories of
customers. "We'll have a wider product line for a wider
customer base," Mr. Rutstein said. As another advantage, he
cited Cedar Group's ability to expand beyond its traditional
distribution centers in Philadlephia, Chicago and Houston by
tapping into the Gardenbolt network.
   Mr. Rutstein declined to make any specific forecasts for
fiscal 1991 sales or earnings, but he indicated that
Gardenbolt would contribute immediately to profit.
   Combined annualized sales would reach about $45 million,
he said. But depending on the timing of the transaction's
close, Gardenbolt may add sales of only about $10 million in
the current fiscal year.
</TEXT>
