<HL>
   BSN Says Subsidiary
   Of Artal Will Acquire
   U.S. Biscuit Operations
</HL>
<DATE>
08/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   F.BSN
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   PARIS -- BSN S.A. said Invus Group Ltd. of the U.S. agreed
to buy the U.S. biscuit operations it put up for sale in May.
   A spokesman for the French food group said he couldn't
disclose the price for the transaction, beyond saying that it
would generate a "substantial capital gain."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Terms of the sale will see Invus Group, a unit of the
closely held Belgian company Artal, take control of BSN's
U.S. biscuit units Mother's and Salerno. The units have
combined annual revenue of about $200 million for a 5.7%
stake of the U.S. market.
   Invus Group will also take over distribution of BSN's Lu
brand in the U.S., but BSN will retain ownership.
   BSN's move out of the U.S. biscuit market reflects its
decision to focus on faster-growing, less-expensive markets
in Asia and Europe, where it has recently been on an
acquisition binge.
   The U.S. pullout doesn't extend to BSN's other U.S.
operations, which include products with higher market shares,
such as Dannon yogurt, Lea &amp; Perrins condiments and Evian
mineral water.
   BSN is France's biggest food group, with consolidated 1989
revenue of 48.7 billion francs ($9.3 billion) and profit of
2.7 billion francs. BSN said Invus Group generates annual
revenue of about $1.3 billion in the U.S., with a large
portion coming from baked goods. It didn't provide further
details.
</TEXT>
