<HL>
   GM Offers to Boost Benefits for Workers
   Laid Off but Proposes No Job Guarantees
   ----
   By Gregory A. Patterson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   GM LABOR F C
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   DETROIT -- General Motors Corp. told the United Auto
Workers union that it is willing to increase the benefits of
the workers it lays off, but the company didn't offer to
enhance job security for any of its 280,000 UAW members.
   Both GM and Ford Motor Co. put formal contract offers on
the bargaining table yesterday in their bid to become the
union's "target" company for negotiating a pattern-setting
contract among the Big Three auto makers. Details of the Ford
proposal couldn't be learned. Chrysler Corp. will make its
contract proposal to the union today.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The UAW is bargaining separately with the three auto
makers for a contract for a total 450,000 UAW members.
   In its proposal to the auto makers, the union has asked
them to keep all their current employees on the job, and pay
them full wages and benefits unless there is a severe threat
to the viability of the company. That proposal is similar to
the practices followed by Japanese auto makers.
   The union is scheduled to select its target company on
Tuesday, and it is widely expected to be GM. The current
three-year contract between the companies and the union
expires Sept. 14.
   Although few details were provided about GM's offer to
boost benefits to laid-off workers, it is known that the
company is willing to increase the amount of money furloughed
workers get, rather than boosting non-dollar benefits. One
current GM program pays laid-off workers up to 95% of their
take-home pay, although that fund is low and benefits have
been reduced.
   GM's proposal included a base-wage increase in the first
year, followed by lump sum-payments at the outset of the two
following years. GM also proposed to improve its pension plan
for UAW retirees.
   Taken together, the moves could help GM reduce its work
force by taking some of the pain out of permanent layoffs it
says are necessary to make it more competitive and by
encouraging some of its older workers to retire once they
become eligible for pensions.
   In return, GM wants UAW officials to approve measures that
would increase productivity in its factories and allow the
company to discharge habitually absent employees.
   The proposal, which GM officials gave to UAW officials in
a closed-door meeting here, marks the first such initial
proposal in which the company offered pay raises to its UAW
employees. Typically, the company doesn't "put money on the
table" until final negotiations began.
   Neither the company nor the union would formally comment
on the details of the proposal. Persons close to the
negotiations, however, did describe the proposal on the
condition of anonymity.
   The pay-increase gambit could sway UAW leaders to select
GM as the target company for negotiations.
   When the UAW chooses one of the Big Three as its target,
it will break off negotiations with the other two auto makers
and press talks with the target company for an accord before
the contract expires.
   "We're serious about going first," a GM executive said,
indicating his company's preference to be the target.
   GM wants to use the talks to get top union leaders to
support their desire for greater flexibility in the plants.
One of GM's chief objectives is to gain support in the UAW
for operating its plants on three shifts. That would allow
the auto maker to boost vehicle output of some models --
assuming demand warranted such a movethereby greatly
increasing a plant's profits.
   The auto maker also wants to stem absenteeism, a serious
problem in GM's factories; it often hovers around 15% of its
hourly work force daily.
   Although GM's wage-increase proposal comes much earlier
than usual, it is structured similar to the current contract.
The pact awarded UAW members a 3% base-wage increase in the
first year, followed by lump-sum payments equal to 3% of
their wages in each of the following two years. GM's current
wage proposal is less than 3%, but it is unlikely that the
final settlement will be identical with the current offer.
   UAW President Owen Bieber attended formal negotiating
sessions with all three auto makers this week. He urged them
to pick up the pace of bargaining and told them that their
offers will play a significant role in determining which
company the union will select as target.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900824-0072
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900824-0072.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   West Germany
   Investigates Firms
   For Sales to Iraq
   ----
   By Timothy Aeppel
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
</IN>
<LP>
   BONN -- By highlighting an investigation against some 60
companies suspected of sending illegal exports to Iraq, the
West German Economics Ministry is trying to deflect criticism
that might be heaped on Bonn in the event of a Middle East
war.
   West German Economics Minister Helmut Haussmann said
yesterday that 25 West German firms were under investigation
for criminal offenses involving the export of weapons and
weapons-related technology to Baghdad. Ministry officials
also confirmed that as many as 34 other companies are
suspected of less serious export violations involving Iraq.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Haussmann said in a statement he plans to tighten
export-control laws sharply and urged West German businesses
"to be especially careful" in their dealings with sensitive
exports. Meanwhile, the West Germans appear to be cracking
down on some of the most serious violators. Last Friday,
authorities arrested seven people suspected of supplying Iraq
with equipment needed to make chemical weapons.
   The arrests and Mr. Haussmann's statements, which didn't
mention any individual or company names or even specify the
illegal exports, come at a sensitive moment for the West
German government. The U.S. is pressuring Bonn to take a more
active role in international military operations aimed at
containing Iraq. But the West Germans insist their Basic Law
prohibits them from sending troops outside the region of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization. West German officials
have said they're considering changing their Basic Law, but
that could prove difficult.
   If the West Germans insist on staying away from the
confrontation, they could face particularly heavy criticism
among their allies for earlier exports that helped Iraq build
up its arsenal. While many countries, including France and
the Soviet Union, supplied weapons to Iraq, German firms are
thought to have spearheaded the development of Baghdad's
chemical-weapons and munitions industries.
   The main question is why Bonn waited so long to take
action. Even Mr. Haussmann concedes that most of the
deliveries occurred "long ago" and only came to his attention
as a result of the Middle East crisis. The first flurry of
concern about questionable West German exports can be traced
to 1988, when Iraq unleashed poison gas on the
Iranian-occupied town of Halabja, where, some analysts
believe, 5,000 Kurdish civilians died.
   West German law bans the sale of any weapons to an area of
conflict, which included Iraq throughout the 1980s. But much
of what was sold falls into a category of goods that is
difficult to control: technology and equipment that have
legitimate commercial uses but that can also be used to
produce weapons. Chemical weapons plants, for instance, are
similar to those used to make pesticides and herbicides. West
Germany began requiring export licenses for such dual-use
equipment only in 1984, and enforcement has been spotty.
   Economics Ministry officials say they have tightened
export controls since early 1989, though they concede some
important regulations are still waiting approval by the West
German parliament. Those measures came in the wake of a
scandal in which West German firms helped Libya develop a
chemical-weapons plant.
   West German officials say they plan to expand the
penalties for those caught circumventing export regulations.
In the wake of the Libyan scandal, West Germany increased the
maximum penalty for those caught selling nuclear or chemical
weapons technology to 10 years from three. Mr. Haussmann now
says he wants to increase the maximum to 15 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900824-0071
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900824-0071.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Credit Markets:
   Investors Scramble for Short-Term U.S. Issues;
   Yield on Benchmark 30-Year Bond Hits 9.13%
   ----
   By Constance Mitchell and Robert Sherman
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN EUROP RJR FHP GCR NG X.DEC KR FRE FNM
</CO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
VETERANS AFFAIRS DEPARTMENT (VET)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- The prospect of an imminent war in the Persian
Gulf battered bonds again, prompting investors to take cover
by buying short-term Treasury notes and bills, the safest
securities available.
   The "flight-to-quality" buying spree was evident in price
quotes posted for long-term securities relative to short-term
securities.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond, for example, fell
3/4 points for a loss of about $7.50 for a bond with a $1,000
face amount. The issue's closing yield jumped to 9.13%, the
highest on the bond since April 14, 1989 when it was 9.14%,
according to Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Short-term Treasury notes and bills, however, ended
unchanged or modestly higher in brisk trading. Dealers said
investors decided to flee the battered stock market and
unwind their money-losing long-term bond positions, using
proceeds to buy short-term securities. As a result, prices
for two-year Treasury notes held firm and the yield was
unchanged at 8.24%. The discount rate on three-month Treasury
bills fell to 7.53% from 7.59% Wednesday.
   William Sullivan, director of money market research at
Dean Witter, said the flight-to-quality buying was first
evident in Tokyo, where investors bailed out of the Japanese
stock market as the Nikkei index of 225 Japanese stocks
plunged 1473.28 points to 23,737.63. That was the
fourth-largest single-day decline in that market.
   In the broader bond market, prices were knocked sharply
lower. Once again, the market's nemesis was rising oil
prices, which investors fear will lead to spiraling inflation
and interest rates. Fixed-income investors dislike inflation
because it cuts the value of their portfolios by reducing the
inflation-adjusted return.
   After hitting a five-year high Wednesday, October oil
futures ended at $31.93 a barrel yesterday, up 71 cents.
   Douglas Schindewolf, vice president and money market
economist at Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co., said investors
are paralyzed by the fear of inflation and "uncertainty about
how high oil could go in the event of an actual armed
conflict."
   Many analysts expect further declines in government
securities, accompanied by higher yields, as long as the
focus remains on oil prices and the Persian Gulf, and not on
economic fundamentals.
   "Forecasting rates is hazardous business with the events
in the Middle East so unpredictable, but I think rates will
grid a bit higher," said James Fralick, an economist at
Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.
   Iraqi President Saddam Hussein has said foreign embassies
in Kuwait must be closed by today, and threatened that
embassy personnel remaining in the oil-rich Arab kingdom
could be stripped of their diplomatic status if they remain.
   President Bush, along with other Western leaders, has said
he will not abide by Mr. Hussein's deadline and will keep the
U.S. Embassy open.
   "Tomorrow's deadline could be the triggerpoint," for the
first clash between U.S. and Iraqi forces, said Mr.
Schindewolf.
   Elsewhere, the Commerce Department today will release
revisions to second-quarter gross national product data.
Economists believe the figure will be revised upward to an
inflation-adjusted annual rate of 1.5% from 1.2%, according
to a Dow Jones Capital Markets Report.
                                                                                                       

   Foreign Bonds
                                                                                                       

   British government bonds continued to recuperate from a
severe oil-related beating while prices in West Germany were
modestly lower.
   But in Japan, which imports all of its oil, the bond
market rout continued. Traders said higher oil prices and a
disappointing government bond auction pushed yields on
Japan's benchmark 10-year bond to the highest levels in
nearly a decade.
   In Tokyo trading, the yield on the benchmark No. 119
10-year bond ended at 8.31% as the issue's price fell to
82.21, down 0.82 points. The yield on nearest bond futures
contract ended at 88.45, down 1.03 points, to yield 8.089%.
That was the highest yield ever for a bond futures contract.
(When calculated using the semiannual compound measure, the
yield on the No. 119 bond ended at 7.60%, according to
Salomon Brothers Inc.)
   As prices sank, the Japanese Finance Ministry attempted to
support the bond market by purchasing 90 billion yen of
10-year bonds. But the purchase had almost no influence on
the market.
   With yields for existing bonds above 8%, traders said
investors weren't interested in buying new 10-year securities
at yesterday's government auction because the 7.53% yield on
the securities, which was set by the government, was
considered unattractive. The offer totaled 800 billion yen.
   Meanwhile, Japan's long-term prime rate is expected to
jump to 8.5% from 7.9% currently because the sell-off in the
Japanese bond market has sharply boosted the costs of funds
for banks.
   Japan's three long-term credit banks, which reset the
long-term prime rate at the end of each month, are expected
to make the decision to boost the long-term prime rate today.
The three banks are Industrial Bank of Japan, Long-Term
Credit Bank of Japan and Nippon Credit Bank.
                                                                                                       

   Treasury Securities
                                                                                                       

   Long-term Treasury bonds were hit hard again, but some
short-term bills and notes ended unchanged or higher.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond ended at a price of
96 1/32 to yield 9.13%, compared with 96 26/32 to yield 9.05%
on Wednesday. The latest 10-year note ended at 98 8/32 to
yield 9% compared with 98 22/32 to yield 8.93%. Two year-note
were unchanged at 99 17/32 to yield 8.24%.
   The Treasury yesterday sold $10.52 billion of 52-week
Treasury bills at an average rate of 7.40%.
   Next week, the Treasury will sell $11.5 billion of new
two-year notes and $8.5 billion of new five-year notes. In
when-issued trading activity yesterday, the two-year notes
were quoted at yields of 8.24% while the five-year notes were
quoted at yields of 8.67%.
   Here are details of yesterday's 52-week Treasury bill
auction:
                                                                                                       

   Rates are determined by the difference between the
purchase price and face value. Thus, higher bidding narrows
the investor's return while lower bidding widens it. The
percentage rates are calculated on a 360-day year, while the
coupon equivalent yield is based on a 365-day year.
                                                                                                       

                                            52-Week Bills
                                                                                                       

   Applications .......................... $24,477,190,000
   Accepted bids ......................... $10,519,670,000
   Accepted at low price .................             48%
   Accepted noncompetitively .............    $611,430,000
   Average price (Rate) ..................  92.518 (7.40%)
   High price (Rate) .....................  92.528 (7.39%)
   Low price (Rate) ......................  92.498 (7.42%)
   Coupon equivalent .....................           7.95%
                                                                                                       

   The bills are dated Aug. 30, and mature Aug. 29, 1991.
                                                                                                       

   Junk, Corporate Issues
                                                                                                       

   The junk-bond market added to its heavy losses as plunging
stock prices pulled bond prices sharply lower.
   Junk bonds plummeted at the opening but managed to stage a
partial rebound at midday after the stock market stabilized.
But when stocks resumed their sharp slide later, junk bonds
followed suit.
   Most higher-quality junk bonds ended one point lower, but
mid-to-lower quality issues suffered even greater losses.
   One of the biggest losers was RJR Nabisco Inc. Its 17.375%
convertible pay-in-kind debentures fell 2 1/8 points to 106
1/4 while its 17% exchangeable pay-in-kind debentures ended 3
3/4 points lower at 80 3/4.
   Elsewhere, Fort Howard Corp.'s 14.125% junior debentures
fell two points to 40, Gaylord Container Corp.'s 13.75%
subordinated debentures dropped three points to an offered
price of 62, and National Gypsum's 14.50% senior subordinated
debentures shed two points to 40.
   The market's better-quality recession-resistant issues,
such as Duracell Holdings Corp. and Kroger Co., remained
firm.
   In the investment-grade market, $600 million in new
corporate debt was priced including a $250 million issue of
five-year issue of Federal Farm Credit Banks notes.
   Strong demand prompted underwriters at Merrill Lynch
Capital Markets to increase the size of the issue twice after
pricing. The notes, which are non-callable for two years,
were priced to yield 8.94%.
   In the secondary market, high-grade bonds also posted
losses, ending the day about 1/2 point lower.
                                                                                                       

   Municipal Issues
                                                                                                       

   Municipal bonds were 3/8 to one point lower.
   In new-issue dealings, seven firms won $550 million of
Texas tax and revenue anticipation notes. The bulk of the
notes were purchased by a Merrill Lynch Capital Markets
group, which priced them with a 6 1/2% coupon to yield 6.18%.
   Among dollar bonds, New Jersey Turnpike Authority's 7.20%
issue due in 2018 was 3/4 point lower at 95 3/4 to yield
7.52%.
                                                                                                       

   Mortgage-Backed Securities
                                                                                                       

   Mortgage-securities prices fell again.
   Government National Mortgage Association's 9 1/2%
pass-through securities for September delivery lost 3/8 point
to 97 5/8, Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.'s 9 1/2% issue
fell 10/32 to 97 9/32 and Federal National Mortgage
Association's 9 1/2% securities were 10/32 lower at 97 26/32.
   The Department of Veterans Affairs offered $293 million of
mortgage pass-through certificates backed by vendee loans,
which are loans issued to finance the sale of VA-owned
properties acquired as a result of loan defaults.
   ---
   Christopher B. Wilcock and Anita Raghavan contributed to
this article.
</TEXT>
