<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report.
                                                                                                       

                        CORPORATES
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. -- $100 million of senior notes, due
Sept. 4, 1993, priced at par to yield 9.30%. The noncallable
notes were priced at a spread of 88 basis points above the
Treasury's three-year note. Rated single-A-2 by Moody's
Investors Service Inc. and single-A by Standard &amp; Poor's
Corp., the issue will be sold through underwriters led by
Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   Rohm &amp; Haas Co. -- $100 million of 9 7/8% notes, due Sept.
1, 2000, priced at 99.53 to yield 9.95%. The non-callable
notes were priced at a spread of 95 basis points above the
Treasury's 10-year note. Rated single-A-1 by Moody's and
single-A by S&amp;P, the issue will be sold through Goldman Sachs
&amp; Co.
                                                                                                       

                         MUNICIPAL
                                                                                                       

   Texas -- $550 million of 12-month tax and revenue
anticipation notes, Series 1990, due Aug. 30, 1991, won by
seven municipal underwriting firms. Final pricing information
as received from each of the underwriters is as follows: $200
million of notes purchased by a Merrill Lynch Capital Markets
group. These notes carry a 6 1/2% coupon and are priced to
yield 6.18%; $150 million notes were won by a BT Securities
Corp. group. These carry a 6 1/2% coupon and are priced to
yield 6.20%.; $100 million of 6 1/2% notes were won by a
Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. group, and are priced to yield 6.20%;
$40 million of 6 1/2% notes were won by a J.P. Morgan
Securities Inc., and are priced to yield 6.18%; $25 million
of 6 1/2% notes were won by a Prudential-Bache Capital
Funding group, and are priced to yield 6.20%; $25 million of
6 1/2% notes also were won by a Smith Barney Harris Upham &amp;
Co. group, and are priced to yield 6.20.%; $10 million of 6
1/2% notes were won by a Bears Stearns &amp; Co. group, and
aren't formally reoffered. The notes are rated MIG-1 by
Moody's and SP-1-plus by S&amp;P.
   State of New York Mortgage Agency Homeowner -- $123
million of mortgage revenue bonds, Series RR, due Oct. 1,
2010 and 2017 and Series SS, due April 1, and Oct. 1,
1992-2000, and due Oct. 1, 2019 and 2022. The bonds are
priced to yield from 6.20% in 1992 to 7.95% in 2022. The
final pricing reflects a repricing that raised the yields on
some issues by five to 10 basis points.
                                                                                                       

                      MORTGAGE-BACKED
                                                                                                       

   American Housing Trust VII -- $293 million of mortgage
pass-through certificates, backed by Vendee Loans, offered by
the Department of Veterans Affairs through First Boston Corp.
Vendee loans are issued to finance the sale of VA-owned
properties acquired as a result of VA loan defaults. The
offering has been structured to yield from 9.337%, a spread
of 95 basis points over the three-year Treasury note, to a
yield of 10.67%%, a spread of 155 basis points over the
30-year Treasury bond. The collateral consists of Vendee
loans with a weighted average coupon rate of 9.462% and
weighted average remaining term to maturity of 28.92 years.
The issue is rated triple-A by S&amp;P and Moody's.
                                                                                                       

                           OTHER
                                                                                                       

   Federal Farm Credit Banks -- $200 million of notes, due
Sept. 7, 1995, priced at par for an initial yield of 8.94%.
The notes, which are non-callable for two years, will be
offered at various prices. The size of the FFCB issue was
increased to $200 million from $150 million after pricing
through underwriters led by Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
The notes were priced at a spread of 31 basis points above
the Treasury's when-issued five-year note.
   Student Loan Marketing Association -- $150 million of
notes, due Sept. 13, 1993, priced at par to yield 8.65%. The
notes, which are non-callable for one year, were priced at a
spread of 23 basis points above the Treasury's one-year note
through underwriters led by Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.
                                                                                                       

                         EUROBONDS
                                                                                                       

   Best Denki Co. (Japan) -- $190 million four-year bonds due
Sept. 14, 1994, with equity warrants, via Nikko Europe.
Interest 4 7/8% annually, issue price at par. Each $5,000
bond carries one warrant exercisable to buy shares at
expected 2.5% premium over closing share price when exercise
terms Aug. 28.
   Fuji Electric Co. (Japan) -- 350 million marks of bonds
with equity-purchase warrants with a fixed 5 1/4% coupon due
Sept. 6, 1994 and priced at par, via Deutsche Bank. Each
5,000 mark bond carries five warrants, exercisable from Oct.
2, 1990 to Aug. 30, 1994, to buy company shares at expected 2
1/2% premium above the closing share price when prices are
fixed Aug. 29. Each 50,000 mark bond carries 50 warrants
attached exercisable under the same terms.
   Copyer Co. (Japan) -- 70 million marks of bonds with
equity-purchase warrants with a fixed 5 1/4% coupon due Sept.
20, 1994 and priced at par, via Bayerische Vereinsbank.
Guaranteed by Sumitomo Bank Ltd. Each 5,000 mark bond carries
one warrant and one certificate with four warrants attached,
exercisable from Oct. 4, 1990 to Sept. 6, 1994, to buy
company shares at an expected premium of 2 1/2% above the
closing share price when prices are fixed Aug. 30.
