900824-0038.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Abreast of the Market:
   Industrials Plunge 76.73, Reacting
   To Collapse in Overseas Markets
   ----
   By Craig S. Smith
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Stocks plunged again as traders rushed to dump
shares before the close of trading.
   The slide took the Dow Jones Industrial Average below the
2500 level, ending at 2483.42, down 76.73 -- its lowest close
since July 1989.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Traders say no one wanted to go out of the market holding
stock for fear that some event overnight could shrink values
further.
   The market opened on a downdraft, reacting to a plunge in
share prices overseas. Tokyo stocks plummeted 5.8% Thursday,
the fourth largest one-day point drop in the market's
history. The Dow Jones industrials lost more than 72 points
in the first hour of trading.
   Even the oil stocks fell, with some issues tumbling back
below their levels before Iraq's invasion of Kuwait, when oil
was about $20 a barrel. Oil stocks, in the face of rising oil
prices, have been resisting the market sell-off. Crude oil
futures yesterday rose to $31.93.
   Investors couldn't blame program trading for the day's
sell-off.
   Lazslo Birinyi, president of Birinyi Associates, says
there was no evidence of program selling in the final hour of
trading when the industrial average plunged an additional 40
points.
   The New York Stock Exchange's "uptick" rule, which
restricts program trading when the Dow Jones industrials fall
50 points, went into effect at 9:54 a.m. EDT, remaining in
effect for the rest of the trading day.
   Standard &amp; Poor's 500-Stock Index dropped 9.49 to 307.06,
the New York Stock Exchange Composite Index fell 5.34 to
168.88, and the Dow Jones Equity Market Index lost 7.79
points to 285.31.
   Only 148 stocks advanced, while 1,645 stocks fell and 242
stocks ended unchanged.
   New York Stock Exchange volume surged to 250,440,000
shares -- bringing the heaviest day of trading since market
players awoke Aug. 2 to the news that Iraq had invaded
Kuwait. Wednesday, 175,550,000 shares were traded.
   Paul Hennessey, vice president of trading at Boston Co.,
said some traders had picked up stocks earlier in the day
hoping for a late session bounce. But when no bounce
materialized, those who held stock rushed to sell before the
close.
   The steep sell-off leaves the market in a position to
rebound early today if there is no bad news overnight, Mr.
Hennessey says. But with the reluctance among traders to hold
stock over the weekend, today's session could prove to be
equally volatile.
   Among the big oil stocks, Exxon gave back 1 3/4 to 49 5/8,
Chevron lost 3 to 75 5/8, Amoco dropped 1 7/8 to 55 3/4 and
Mobil lost 2 3/8 to 62 7/8.
   While analysts continue to consider the energy sector one
of the safest havens within the stock market, they say
investors looking to buy now should pick their stocks with
care.
   Bernard J. Picchi, oil analyst at Salomon Brothers,
cautions that many of the major oil companies have reached
price-earnings valuations well above their peaks during the
last oil-price surge of 1979-1980 when oil reached $40 a
barrel. And many of those companies are now more dependent on
income from their chemical businesses than they were back
then, he says.
   Higher oil prices are likely to squeeze the profits of
petrochemical and plastics operations, Mr. Picchi says, while
a general economic downturn could hurt the markets for those
products in general.
   "In 1980, almost no one {of the major oil companies} was
making money from chemicals, while last year, chemicals
contributed about 16% to the income of the nine largest oil
companies," Mr. Picchi says.
   He is recommending a handful of major oil companies and
refiners that could manage real gains, or will at least fall
less than other stocks.
   Atlantic Richfield and Texaco are Mr. Picchi's picks,
which he says are still cheap relative to other oil stocks
and have less exposure to the chemicals business.
   He also likes refiners Diamond Shamrock, Ashland Oil and
Valero Energy, pointing out that they are likely to benefit
from diminished refining capacity around the world in the
wake of the Middle East turmoil.
   Mr. Picchi estimates that the world has already lost about
1.2 million to 1.3 million barrels a day of refined products
such as gasoline, kerosene and home-heating oil because of
the embargo against Kuwaiti and Iraqi production.
   Meanwhile, U.S. refineries are operating at about 95% of
their capacity, he says.
   "The bottom line is that we are probably going to see
higher profit margins in refining for a longer period of time
than we would have thought possible before," he says.
   Texaco fell 3 5/8 to 60 1/8, while Atlantic Richfield rose
1/8 to 138 1/2. Diamond Shamrock lost 1/2 to 21 1/4, Ashland
Oil fell 1/2 to 31 1/4, and Valero Energy slipped 3/8 to 15.
   Eli Lilly slid 2 to 68 1/2, leading the most active list
on volume of more than 4.6 million shares. Medtronic said the
U.S. Court of Appeals vacated a lower court finding that
Medtronic infringed patents held by Eli Lilly. Medtronic fell
1 5/8 to 74 5/8.
   Insurance and financial services provider Transamerica
tumbled 3 3/8, or nearly 11%, to 30 on volume of more than
1.8 million shares. The company said it couldn't explain why
its stock has fallen further than the rest of the market. The
company said it still expects to report a strong year.
   The Federal National Mortgage Association lost only 1/8 to
26 5/8 on volume of more than 3.6 million shares. Fannie
Mae's announcement that it will buy back as much as $500
million of its common stock and warrants lent support to its
share price.
   Auto stocks fared better than the rest of the market.
General Motors lost only 3/8 to 36 1/4, Ford fell 1 1/8 to 33
1/8 and Chrysler dropped 1/4 to 12. Sales of U.S.-made cars
were better than expected in mid-August.
   Harken Energy rose 1/4 to 3 3/8. International Rectifier
added 3/8 to 8 3/8. The semiconductor maker reported profit
of 18 cents a share for the fiscal year ended in June,
compared with a loss of $1.13 a share in fiscal 1989. The
company said it expects "double-digit" revenue growth in
1991, with continued improvement in its operating profit.
   The American Stock Exchange Market Value Index lost 8.54
to 315.85. Volume rose to 24,850,000 shares, compared with
16,570,000 shares Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900824-0037
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900824-0037.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Many Southern Baptists May Withhold
   Large Sums From Conservate Coffers
   ----
   By R. Gustav Niebuhr
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<LP>
   ATLANTA -- Some 3,000 dissident Southern Baptists are
discussing plans to withhold millions of dollars in annual
contributions from the Southern Baptist Convention, in what
some religious experts see as a first step toward their
pulling out of America's largest Protestant denomination
altogether.
   The Baptists, who are holding a three-day meeting in
Atlanta, represent the moderate faction of the denomination.
In recent years, they have become increasingly angered at the
conservative fundamentalist faction that has ruled the
denomination.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In discussions currently under way, the moderates are
proposing to set up a trust fund into which their churches
would funnel the money that is now being sent to the
denomination's coffers in Nashville, Tenn. The trust fund
would then spend the money on the moderates' own causes, such
as a possible new seminary. Using the trust fund, they could
bypass causes supported by the denomination's fundamentalist
leaders, such as the creation of a new religious right lobby
in Washington.
   The plan poses a direct threat to the denomination's
financial health -- and its conservative political clout --
because moderate churches have traditionally contributed far
more money to Southern Baptists headquarters than have
fundamentalist churches. Moderates estimate they contribute
at least 60%. This year's budget is about $137 million.
   The denomination's president, the Rev. Morris Chapman,
couldn't be reached for comment, nor could the denomination's
top financial officers. However, in a statement issued last
week, several top Southern Baptist leaders strongly warned
churches not to stop sending donations to headquarters,
warning that a lack of funds could lead to mass layoffs and
the shutdown of programs.
   Since fundamentalists took control of the denomination in
1979, moderates have charged that they have not been given a
fair voice in denomination affairs. Those who don't hold
certain conservative political and religious views -- such as
favoring school prayer, strictly opposing abortion, upholding
a literal interpretation of the Bible -- are penalized. They
have been shut out of leadership positions, and some have
even been fired.
   Angry at that situation, some moderates over the past year
have responded by cutting back on their contributions. As a
result, the denomination has had to curtail projects and lay
off some employees. In the event of an outright financial
rebellion, the denomination could find itself perilously
short on cash to support its vast missionary force and six
seminaries. The financial setback could also badly hurt the
denomination's powerful image as the religious right
powerhouse, an image that prompted conservative politicians
to court leading Baptist preachers and consider their
fundamentalist views in the 1980s.
   In addition, a declaration of financial independence by
moderates would inevitably generate momentum "toward the
forming of a new denomination," said Glenn Hinson, a
professor of church history at Southern Baptist Theological
Seminary in Louisville, Ky., who is attending the meeting.
Others said they expected the moderates to break from the
denomination as early as next year.
   One of the meeting's organizers, the Rev. William
Scarborough, pastor of National Heights Baptist Church in
Fayetteville, Ga., said the possibility of a schism seems to
appeal mostly to younger Baptists. "But for people like
myself, who have served in the Southern Baptist Convention
all our lives, it's really hard to think of going with
another church," he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900824-0036
</DOCNO>
