<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   New York Post's Salembier
   Quits as Paper's President
</HL>
<DATE>
08/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS
</CO>
<LP>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The owner of the New York Post announced
the resignation of Valerie Salembier as president of the
newspaper.
   Ms. Salembier, the former publisher of TV Guide, was named
to the post in April 1989.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Peter Kalikow, the Post's owner and publisher, said he
would reassume the title of president.
   Ms. Salembier, who supervised business, advertising and
circulation, said she felt it was time "to move forward to
new challenges and opportunities."
   "She has successfully structured a business operation
which has effectively positioned the New York Post for sales
and profit growth in the '90s," Mr. Kalikow said.
   Last November, the Post discontinued its eight-month-old
Sunday edition, which failed to attract sufficient
advertisers or readers and lost millions of dollars.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900824-0014
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900824-0014.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
08/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   THE U.S. FACED a crucial test in Kuwait over Iraq's threat
to close embassies.
   As the Bush administration's war of nerves with the Iraqis
intensified over Saddam Hussein's order that Western
embassies in Kuwait shut down today -- and with most vowing
they will remain open -- the U.S. acted to forge a global
effort to aid nations hurt by the embargo of Iraq. U.S.
officials analyzed the needs of Jordan, Egypt and Turkey, and
Bush reportedly asked Japan's Kaifu to help some nations.
Israeli military sources said Jordanian officers have been
training Iraqis to use U.S.-made Hawk anti-aircraft missiles
captured from Kuwait. And Kuwaiti officials said Baghdad has
mined most of Kuwait's oil wells and threatened to blow them
up if there is an attack.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi television broadcast a tape of Saddam Hussein
talking to British captives, including several children. The
U.S. and Britain expressed outrage.
   ---
   ARMENIA'S PARLIAMENT PASSED a declaration of independence
from Moscow.
   The southern republic's legislators voted to assume
control over defense, foreign and economic policy, and
resolved to reunite with the disputed territory of
Nagorno-Karabakh. While the statement stopped short of
calling for a complete break with the Kremlin, Armenia became
the fifth of the 15 Soviet republics to move toward
secession.
   Estonia began formal talks with Moscow on separation, and
the republic of Turkmenia declared the right to overturn
Soviet laws on its territory.
   ---
   Black nationalist leader Mandela urged the South African
government to deploy troops in black townships near
Johannesburg, as members of the Zulu and Xhosa tribes clashed
for the 12th day with spears, axes and knives. President de
Klerk said he would announce steps today to stop the
fighting, which has claimed over 500 lives.
   ---
   A panel of federal judges recommended that television
cameras be allowed in federal courtrooms on an experimental
basis. The experiment, which requires the approval of the
U.S. Judicial Conference, would allow cameras into civil
proceedings in six district courts and two appeals courts for
three years.
   ---
   Researchers halted the growth of colon cancer cells in a
test tube by replacing a damaged gene with its normal
version. The experiment supports a theory that certain genes
normally prevent uncontrolled, malignant cell growth and that
cancer arises when these "tumor suppressor" genes are
inactivated.
   ---
   FDA scientists documented their belief that a synthetic
growth hormone designed to boost cows' milk production poses
no health risk. The agency released a review of over 120
studies to support its statements that milk and meat from
cows treated with bovine growth hormone, which is still not
approved, are safe.
   ---
   The West German government welcomed East Germany's
decision to fix Oct. 3 as the date the two nations will
merge, expressing relief that bickering about the timing of
unification was over. The East German Parliament approved the
date late Wednesday, and it requires no ratification from
Bonn.
   ---
   Moderate Southern Baptists discussed plans to withdraw
millions of dollars in contributions from the Southern
Baptist Convention. The group of 3,000 dissidents, meeting in
Atlanta, are angry at the conservative fundamentalist faction
that has ruled the denomination for over a decade.
   ---
   NASA said it replaced part of the computer memory of the
Venus-orbiting Magellan spacecraft, which broke off radio
contact temporarily Wednesday for the second time within a
week. Magellan is on a $744 million mission to use its radar
to make pictures and maps of the planet's surface.
   ---
   West African troops set sail from Sierra Leone to enforce
a cease-fire in Liberia, where a rebel army led by Charles
Taylor threatened to fight them. The West African Economic
Community, which mobilized the 3,000 soldiers, emphasized
that the task force was on a peaceful mission to halt the
eight-month-old civil war.
   ---
   Israel's finance minister said he would ask the U.S. for
more military and other aid when he visits Washington next
month. But Yitzhak Modai wouldn't say how much additional
assistance is sought by the Israeli government, which
currently receives about $3 billion annually from the U.S.
   ---
   Died: Harold Thorkilsen, 64, former president of the Ocean
Spray cranberry-growers cooperative, in Osterville, Mass.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
